The Data

The dataset for this assignment was gathered in 1970 in the Boston metropolitan area. Each row corresponds to one US Census tract. These are geographic areas with a few thousand people used by the U.S. government in its decennial census of the population. (The help menu entry refers to towns in a few places. These should read census tracts.) The dataset is the Boston dataset in the MASS package.

Note that the set of entries here is not a sample of a larger population of Boston census tracts. It represents all census tracts in Boston (Though each entry itself may be a sample of the larger population in that tract.) We also can not say that Boston represents the entire US, since regions differ. For our purposes, let us assume that these census tracts are a sample of all census tracts in urban areas in the northeastern United States.

Question 4 (10 Points)

Assume that urban northeastern US property tax rates are currently around 1.054%. (Actually, this is Boston. Just go with it.) We would like to know if urban northeastern US property tax rates are higher today than they were in 1970.

Set up (but dont run it yet) a hypothesis test to examine this question. What are your null and alternative hypotheses? What is the cut-off for a p-value that you will use to reject the null?

Q4 Response

Null Hypothesis: The property tax rates in 1970 in Boston are 1.054%.

Alternative Hypothesis: The property tax rates in 1970 in Boston are lower than 1.054%.

Cut-off p-value (alpha): 0.05

Question 5 (10 Points)

Use the traditional method, with a test-statistic, to calculate the p-value for the hypothesis test you wrote out in Question 4. Write your conclusion in a few complete sentences that would make sense to a random Boston citizen.

boston_tax <- boston %>% mutate(tax_rate = tax/100) 

boston_tax %>% summarize(mean_tax = mean(tax_rate), std_tax = sd(tax_rate))
##   mean_tax  std_tax
## 1 4.082372 1.685371
t.test(boston_tax$tax_rate, mu = 1.054, alternative = "less")
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  boston_tax$tax_rate
## t = 40.419, df = 505, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is less than 1.054
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##      -Inf 4.205837
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  4.082372
pt(40.41979, 505)
## [1] 1

Q5 Response

n = 506 x-bar = 4.082372 mu= 1.054 s = 1.685371 SE = s/n^1/2 = 0.074923 df = n-1 = 505

t = [(x-bar) - mu]/SE = 40.41979

p-value= 1-pt = 1

Since the p-value is greater than 0.05 (alpha), we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Hence, the property tax rates in 1970 in Boston are equal to 1.054%.

Q7 Response

The probability values of zn(proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.), rm(average number of rooms per dwelling), dis(weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres) and rad(index of accessibility to radial highways) are less than the pre-determined probability value. Hence, these traits are not significantly related to the high-crime areas in Boston(statistically insignificant).

The R^2 value is 0.416.

Question 8 (10 Points)

Remember how the distribution of per capita crime looked? This means that the data is right-skewed. In cases like this we might try log-transforming the data. If we find a stronger statistical relationship with the log-transformed data, then there might be an exponential process that generated the original data. (Because logarithms undo exponents.) For example if you suspect that the relationship between variables x and y is \(y=a*b^x\), then the log-transformed equation is \(log(y)=log(a)+x*log(b)\) or, rewriting the constants, \(log(y)=A + Bx\). So x and log(y) will be linearly related, and we can do a linear regression. For more more details on logarithms, you can check out: https://www.statisticshowto.datasciencecentral.com/probability-and-statistics/statistics-definitions/logarithms/

Q8 Response

The probability values of zn(proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.), rm(average number of rooms per dwelling), nox(nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)), age(proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940) and rad(index of accessibility to radial highways) are less than the pre-determined probability value. Hence, these traits are not significantly related to the high-crime areas in Boston(statistically insignificant).

The R^2 value is 0.866.

Question 9 (10 points)

Compare the R^2 values of the two regressions from Q7 and Q8. Which regression seems to have a stronger relationship? Should we use crim or log_crim in future analysis? (You should also be able to support your explanation by looking at graphs of the residuals for each regression. Though you dont have to do that here.)

b1_regression_points <- get_regression_points(b1)

  geom_point(size = 0.8) +

B1_regression_points <- get_regression_points(B1)

  geom_point(size = 0.8) +
  labs(x = "logcrim", y = "Residual") + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, col = "red", size = 1)

Q9 Response

Since the R^2 value of B1 is greater than R^2 value of b1 and more closer to 1, the regression model of log_crim seems to have stronger relationship. The regression predictions of B1 model is a better fit than of b1 model. Therefore, we should use log_crim for future analysis.
